The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Perhaps
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Perhaps he won’t be waiting longer.
The fact that Czech cell phone providers are working among the most expensive in Europe has been reported on Mobil.cz.
This was confirmed by the telecommunications agency ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the European Commission’s last steps in the regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation is likely – for some customers of Czech mobile providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really makes a fighting proposition.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical that there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to complain that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák often agrees that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network doesn’t have a lot of chances anymore (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies either).
But there is another option – a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, to which the classical mobile providers also had to react.
Before companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar voices as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, it doesn’t take long to look for examples.
In February this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to work effectively, virtual vendors need much fewer customers than a classic vendor.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually stand out as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-clichée target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating company of this virtual provider.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept could take foot in the Czech Republic as well as in Poland.
Vodafone’s press spokesman Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual vendors are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering.”
In the Czech Republic, mobile providers say
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be mobile.
"While we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look particularly hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries of our region,” said Jana Studničková, press spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a phone call to Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Its interest in launching a virtual mobile provider has already shown for a long time the GTS Novera group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile providers.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve progress in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, the group’s press spokesman.
Maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not expect that there is room in the Czech Republic for a full-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market has large specifics compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and reputable project in this area,” says in his statement to Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other providers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile’s press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová rarely agrees with O2’s statement: “So far, we haven’t found a viable and beneficial project on both sides to build on.”
And she adds: “In the T-Mobile network, hardly any virtual provider will appear by the end of the year.
At this moment we would have to have a concrete offer in order to be able to think so shortly."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of division of costs and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we see as the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The approach of the mobile providers is easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, which would lead to declining prices and thus to a decrease in profits.
So why should one make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something also proves the long go and go about the emergence of U:fon.
Perhaps the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ came from the company T-Mobile at the time when U:fon came on the market.
This is evidenced by the information available to the public from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is suitable as an argument why one should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile provider.
Taking into account the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services."
However, in view of this approach of the mobile providers, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulators is amazed.
This is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in Czech, unlike in the UK and other highly developed countries.
It is exclusively the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, referred to his very typical attitude to this whole problem.
“The entry of a virtual mobile provider on the market would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider on renting the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential prospects was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic suppliers,” said Kristián Chalupa, from the Department of External Relations of the UOHS.
From the representatives of the providers, such a formulation would not surprise.
This is more than worrying by an authority to represent consumer interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses his position in the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual providers work normally, it is observed that their entry to the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
Probably, however, pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction do not belong to the interests of the UOHS.
Really shocking in this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile carriers, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely equal gasoline price at the gas stations is surely only coincidence and the consequence of a harsh competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs in this matter indicating action against competition, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions in the market.
“The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual providers are likely to be missing from the telecommunications regulator,” Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators hold a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - for a virtual provider to enter the market it is always necessary to obtain the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not follow this argument, it should at least be a warning for the UOHS that three mobile carriers act strikingly similarly.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) demonstrate that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act failed to enforce the extension of ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of professionals had promised to improve the situation.
The UOHS representatives need to know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It can be done when no one looks
First of all, the functioning of some pseudovirtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, is not considered.
It is companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but that are only partly public.
These are usually companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach selected ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special pricing offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, it can be a violation of the contractual terms, which we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the corresponding company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not be talked about with the responsible of the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such an action.
Indeed, profits from the activities of these companies do not flow to them to be negligible, at the same time they are not affected - unlike the actual virtual providers - by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite the fact that the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone doesn’t run on their name, so they can’t have it fully as the normal customers of the mobile providers.”
But this alone should at least seem strange.
Another question is opened for the UOHS.
If mobile providers close their eyes before such an action, why do they lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has fairly strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not wish, it does not have to satisfy the providers’ statement that they would not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As the text has already emphasized several times, the entry of virtual vendors on the market led to a significant price drop in the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence virtually more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies intervened in these moments, which by no means tried to safeguard the interests of the mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and further followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are taking the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that uncertainty in competences is more than favourable in these cases.
But let’s not throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon appears, the Czech mobile market may soon get back in motion.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile provider, the UOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other prospects.
And then the Czechs will finally not call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek, on the occasion of the Czech State Day, presented the new recordings of the national anthem Where my home country is.
The hymn was newly recorded by the National Theatre’s orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
Four versions are available - with male or female solo singing, in choral recording and in an instrumental version.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka took over the song.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server, you can listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful anthems.
Earlier he told Czech radio that he had selected for the solo singers with young, representative voices that are distinctive and popular.
"From the beginning, I tried to keep a clear diction with both of them and then with the choir, so that you can understand the text well, so that it can be harmonized," says the conductor.
The Czech national anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj first sounded in 1834 on the stage of the stand theatre in the originally Czech piece Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music originating from František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously accepted it.
The first strofe of the song became an organic part of the national anthem after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
One of the seven state symbols remained after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
