The Prague transport companies also transport on a chip on Wednesday for the first time
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will enter the history of Prague’s transport companies as a date on which the first passengers who carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket will enter a metro, tram or bus.
These can currently be purchased by about a hundred thousand people who own the OpenCard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it simultaneously played on their chip card at the information centers and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holeší, Andýl, Rozty.
The coupons are also available since yesterday via the Internet on the websites of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the internet sales can really forget the output window at the metro stations, where they had to wait regularly for their paper tickets in long queues so far.
They buy the coupon over the internet, which is played on the open card at one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these locations, travellers are also provided with a desk with trained staff, which advises interested parties on internet purchases and also plays the coupon on the map," says project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, you can also place the electronic coupons on the open card on self-service machines, which are attached in some subway vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminded of ticket deductors, the passengers may have already noticed them at the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five in the city, but by the end of the year it is expected to be eighty," added Opatrný.
The coupon is controlled by an automated machine instead of the driver.
Operating the machines that will work from tomorrow is easy.
All you have to do is introduce the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon plays on its own.
Electronic coupons will apply not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area from tomorrow.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which mostly the inhabitants from the municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia reach the capital.
“In the trains that belong to Prague’s integrated transportation, the train attendants have readers that allow them to check the validity of the coupons by time and zone,” explains Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid, which compiles the schedules for the Prague transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the checkout with the driver.
On boarding, the chip card must not only be displayed to the driver, but the open card must be placed at a marked place on the side of the checkout.
Thus, the driver controls the validity of the coupons played.
“If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons played, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information,” Drápal said.
A passenger who does not drive on suburban buses and does not know when the coupon ends, can in turn go to the self-service machines, where the coupons are played up on the map.
Here the information on the validity of your documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudets called for a referendum from the United States
In 1945, the Sudet Germans had requested the association of the Bohemian Forest with the United States.
This is evident in a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
