Rats have feelings too.
Does a rat or sheep flee in danger mean that they also feel fear?
The neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: many animals also have feelings.
But how can we see if they feel the same when they behave like us?
The internet magazine "Edge" has been publishing contributions from famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having been able to prove this so far where we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and address questions of feeling, or generally of consciousness, we enter inevitable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it stands dead, flees, or attacks.
People behave similarly, which some scientists suggests is a similar subjective experience.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in the execution / control functions).
This broad region is much higher developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely missing from other creatures.
At least with those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since so much of his experience is linked to language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness does not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever it may be, probably differs very much from most of our consciousness states.
This is why it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it is not possible to measure or analyze, because of the special hardware, on the basis of our own experience, then his exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of my speeches refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness, which should be more scientifically accessible.
One could study the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But with this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, we rely more on the neural correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the achievement of visualization.
What is the result of the sensations?
I draw them back to the fact that an emotional system like the one of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies work memory.
In this way, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that distinguish primates and in particular humans.
Connected with the linguistic nature, fine levels of sensation arise because we can differentiate and categorize states with the help of words and grammar, in order to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio says that sensations from more primitive activities in the body-sensitive regions of the cortex and brain stem arise similar to Jaak Pankseep, which, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may be involved in cross-gender sensations.
Purely theoretically, I cannot oppose this, but I think it is unproven.
Pankseep argues that what appears like fear in rats and humans probably feels like this in both cases: But how can one check whether rats and humans feel the same if they behave similarly?
Does a sting flee in danger if she also feels fear?
In my eyes, pure behavioral similarity cannot prove equality of experience.
Neural comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain strains, but scratching doesn’t even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove this for humans, how did you want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even shreds (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove that.
And because their sensations probably differ fundamentally from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, there is progress on the neural level, as long as rats and humans measure the same.
How I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, even feelings, I do not know if they exist.
You may think this is short-sighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than walking against a wall constantly.
