This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the specialized lessons.
Ms. Mikels, who rejected the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico.
“It works,” she said, “it works for us.”
Would Obama take a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school’s achievements would make it easy to answer this question, but the educational policy positions within its own party (the national image unions have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s response uncertain.
