The pride and the hardships in the lives of the black people, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden among the outbreaks of the amusement parks in the outskirts of Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, loud and gigantic drives, lies a quiet town where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first completely black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurstons, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet pitches, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guava, 2 schools and no prison."
Nowadays it is a pilgrimage place.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, the city that describes it – and which made it a tourist destination by including it in the Florida Travel Guide, produced by the Federal Writer Project at the time of depression – is and remains in many ways a place of the very special variety.
Eatonville is as independent, generous and private as in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even nowadays, in a year in which a black presidential candidacy, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open conversation about racial conditions, many here are still sick of being watched by outsiders.
“We are very careful about how our history is told,” says Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and a member of the town’s oldest church.
It must be true."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historic example of the black movement and a municipality of nearly 2,400 inhabitants, in which the poverty rate is twice as high as the country’s average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural south, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and watchful.
And that's how the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in words, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road leading through the often forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Freak like Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Beyond the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, although he can hardly read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of Widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and what-always-fits hours."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
This was certainly not a guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
“Zora described things as they were,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls, who eternalized the Hurston by quoting the men singing songs about their beauty full of sexual allusions.
She added, “Some people didn’t like this.”
Here, Hurtson is still remembered as a lively eccentric who regularly returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came to the city, she usually did it without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and clothed in pants, in a city that itself today imagines something on her venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, while many despised them.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he swinged in his chair, on a back-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were lost.
Together with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no great memorial, no public readings in a large style.
“I don’t think they understood their contribution to the world or their heritage at all,” says Valerie Boyd, author of Wrapped in Rainbows, a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to set a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the municipality's slow two-lane main road.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts.
The proposal was submitted as Eatonville still recovered from a difficult phase in his history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixture brought hatred into the community.
“At that time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff on the people sitting away,” Mr. Franklin said.
“There was even a woman who was killed in the process.
They threw a watermelon out of the car.”
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand to force integration, calling its decision in Brown's case against the school council "insulting instead of respecting my race."
Nowadays, residents say that although the abolition of racial separation was positive in some respects, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - they hugged their teacher in the morning and hugged their teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the non-profit group to protect the Eatonville community.
She added that this could be maintained for as long as teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"We didn't embrace his white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural gap," Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped create space for more Zora Neale Hursttons – black writers, actors and artists who overlooked prejudices, just like she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, “How can anyone refuse the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, the writer Alice Walker set out on her way to Hurst's nameless grave and began fighting for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-praised Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was found on the book shelves, and made it again part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came exactly at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter once again stood in the light of the public.
And this time, Hurst's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The municipality began in 1988 with the planning of a Hurston Festival to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and many return every January for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road plans.
“The plans of a five-lane highway lived the city, accelerated the whole thing at peak speed, awakening real citizen pride,” Nathiri said.
Ms. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project has contributed to a change in the city’s self-image.
There were more and more railroads, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who went to church here since 1993, and locals began to reappreciate the past.
Eatonville was included in the national historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Nowadays, Eatonville remains a peculiarity in Florida: just 6 miles from Orlando’s city centre, it can sometimes feel like a back lane in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90% black nowadays.)
Foreigners looking for the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, permission is necessary in advance and certain things – such as the wall painting of Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white one and representing black men in field work – must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a courageous, self-confident teacher with a preference for dark red, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time as the Hurston Festival grew bigger, an increased degree of home pride was also born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and as proud, creative and laborious, silly and mixed as any other race and people group in America.
It is the sincere love of this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, which he says might need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“Most of the people who just go through here will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” Alondra Kenon said on a Sunday after church.
“But if you actually stop and look at your history for a moment, it’s a very beautiful city.”
