Drivers who may fall back due to alcohol levels will have to install the `Alcolock'.
The authority orders the driver who had three official penalties for alcohol levels to install in his car this system, which prohibits him from starting the car in a drunk state.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the Attorney General’s Office, which they say is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose is to re-socialize the driver, which is why he gets a course for the re-education of traffic behaviour.
In addition to the General Prosecutor’s Office, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for Automotive Safety will also participate.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of drivers who were shown more than once because of driving under the influence of alcohol sat back on the wheel.
The `alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents auto start when the driver has taken an alcohol test; or when an alcohol concentration that is higher than allowed is detected.
It costs more than 1,000 euros, the costs are borne by the person who imposes the penalty.
In this context, a study conducted in the U.S. in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of breaches of the rules in the first year after their introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved every year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, a legal reform can be implemented in the usual way, and yet a reform of the Fundamental Law is demanded, which is necessary for the law enforcement process.
The device is still not available in any store in the Spanish markets, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the House of Representatives will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers’ Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
