Interview - From Blood That Became Safe Again
Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its founding, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had all the reasons to be pleased because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained the public trust that had been severely shaken by the scandal of the infested blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service were infected with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada initiated a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and developing guidelines to prevent a renewed catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to issue his report, several provinces set up a committee at the time to develop a new system for managing blood stored in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were founded in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started working, barely 38% of people had confidence in Quebec’s blood-conserved system, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the tremendous efforts to improve the safety of blood conserves and by working in this area for the next few years, we have regained public confidence,” she says, before proudly emphasizing that in early 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec’s population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps aware that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec acts on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman, who has been in charge since its foundation in 1998.
“And we had no idea whether this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied if you do not know this and if a disease is only progressing slowly, as is obviously the case with the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by brain degeneration, which inevitably leads to death.
Thus, in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago it was proven without any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event showed us that the principle of caution that we applied is quite meaningful.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which allow to detect the occurrence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST allowed to shorten the incubation time between the time when the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and you could not recognize it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of AIDS transmission through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, it means that you would have to distribute 12 million blood stocks before anyone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 conserved blood each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV was transmitted via a conserved blood.
I believe that you can feel comfortable with getting a blood transfusion or prescribing it to restore health," says Hema-Quebec's Chief Executive Officer.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
Only last year has the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects through the blood.
“We need to monitor continuously,” continues Dr. Décary before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec needs to provide adequate supply in addition to a secure supply.
“The demand is rising because the population is aging.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also affects the blood donor network, which on average only 3% of Quebec's inhabitants are eligible for blood donation.'
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the suitability criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who supply their blood will not be accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread will be excluded from blood donation for a year.
`With these 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep it and make it become regular donors.
“Life is so hectic nowadays that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” said Francine Decary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only conserved blood but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which are used almost exclusively for serious fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public umbilical cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to take out more than a thousand per year.
“We should probably start making it available for transplantation early next year,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood reduction as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it,” because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
