Rescue for Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis, which has been shaking Wall Street for months, has yet to be adopted by the two congressional chambers.
The main contents are: Improved MEP control over the practical implementation of the plan, new mechanisms to secure the repayment of the public funds used, new provisions to curb the number of houses confiscated due to defaults, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the senior employees of the supported companies.
U.S. Secretary of Finance Henry Paulson, Chamber President Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative present in the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news, after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be market-effective,” said Bush Administration representative Henry Paulson.
“It was all to protect the real economy and the American people from the Wall Street currency crisis,” she said.
“This is the basic point: if we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos and unrest in the daily lives of Americans will be enormous,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, for fear of the effect that a renewed failure would have had on the mood of investors.
The deadline agreed was the opening of the market this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who were only involved late in the negotiations, showed themselves rather as proponents of the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the fact that they had to be met in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on adding certain arrangements, especially those that allow owners to retain their homes, and those that concern the salaries of senior employees of state-rescued companies.
“When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain persons, that is nothing you could congratulate yourself on.
But these measures are necessary,” he said on American television channels.
When he was asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied, “I would like to know the details first, but I hope it.
“The guidelines I have read show that this is one thing that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing at all is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan is aimed at paying taxpayers’ money.
It comes 14 months after a crisis, triggered by the burst of a real estate bubble, which initially led to the collapse of high-risk mortgage loans (subprime) before it expanded to further forms of more widespread bonds (PCAA), and finally resulted in a freezing of financial power and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
A group of Republican deputies failed last week’s first attempt to reach an agreement.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain 'toxic' assets of societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not purchased, it is believed to escape the blind alley.
To round out the viewpoints for everyone in Congress, a warrant has also been added that if the government makes losses with this program within five years, it can then collect new taxes in order to recover its invested capital.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion dollars, to which another 100 billion can be added if the president considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion dollars must be approved by Congress in a re-vote.
In return for his aid, Washington receives shares in the supported companies, which bring dividends to it in the case of profits, and which it can sell again when the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the opportunity to halt the seizure procedures in respect of the housing bound to the real estate loans affected by this plan, as well as to set deadlines for the repayment and compensation to be paid to the executive officers of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the House of Representatives to vote on it today, and then the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet sure that their plan will get green light.
In fact, yesterday there were other votes against this plan, both on the part of the Republicans and the Democrats.
“Obviously Washington doesn’t understand us,” Republican Scott Garett, a member of the House’s financial commission, said to his voters.
“Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that is to ask taxpayers to check out."
Democratic MP Brad Sherman, head of a congressional group called "the Caucus of the Skeptics," presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred excellent economic professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to tell us: We ask Congress not to be put under pressure and carefully consider which path to go,” he said yesterday.
At the same time, we have once again received evidence in Europe that it is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for €11.2 billion (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, who is in great difficulty since she lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion dollars) in the crisis due to the high-risk real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
“This is not lost money,” said the Dutch Minister of Finance, Wouter Bos.
In order to compensate, we receive a voting right and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what savers and households appreciate now that uncertain times are announcing.'
During this time, on the other side of the Channel, the British government was about to nationalize another bank in distress from the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all current loans from Bank Bradford and Bringley, including over 41 billion ($75.5 billion) from real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the UK bank’s branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank after Northern Rock to nationalize the British government since the start of the financial crisis.
