The Psychology of Over-Offering - Or Why We Are Ready to Pay More
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bidding.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now managed to discover the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the Science magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an eBay auction, and are therefore willing to pay even overpriced prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lottery while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the volunteers were investigated using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the players were able to win money, however, an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain bark, was measured among the losers of the auction, in which the overtaking of the opponent plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore believed that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To support their thesis, the economists in the research group also conducted research to track the money.
In this case, three groups should be offered against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their operations.
Another group was also promised $15 reward in case they emerged as winners from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that the emphasis on one was on winning, while on the other was on losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the group playing against losing were prepared for higher stakes than those in the control and win-win groups.
“These findings can be derived from no previous economic theory.
In fact, these have justified the behaviours observed at auctions so far only with the joy of profiting or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York's Economic Faculty.
Hepatitis: When to visit the doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated at a hundred thousand in the country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellowness are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from one another.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vagina or saliva).
Travellers are advised to vaccinate against viruses A and B at any rate, there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by unwellness, weakness, abdominal pain and breach.
After that, yellowness occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine darkens, and recovery can last up to two to three weeks.
Around 1 million people worldwide die annually from the far more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected people are on drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insanely destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the family doctor for the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognised in a timely manner, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated, thus preventing the risk of infection and preventing the onset of cancer.
Sept. 30 is World Hepatitis Day, hosted by patient representations worldwide for the first time in 2004.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, its origin and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
Recent research shows that religious belief acts as a kind of “pain remedy” that has already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: it was investigated to what extent belief in God affects human pain, the British journal Telegraph reported.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electro-shock while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the believers were able to eliminate most of the pain.
A brain scan technology even proved that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project involving philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university.
During the attempt, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand, which gave off the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would elicit some sort of religious transe, while selecting da Vinci’s image, because it barely differed from the other paintings and was felt as reassuring.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, receiving a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages during that time, while looking at either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that when they saw the Mother of God, they felt “secure” as if they were “careful” and they felt “rest and peace.”
While looking at the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in sight.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be caused with other, strongly-acting images among the atheists, if you only had to find the corresponding photo.
“We should find an image that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“Practicing faith should change our personality, and it does in many cases,” Wright said.
After these outstanding results, only the question remains what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another similar painter would have on the pain regulation of the believers.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
