Intelligent car mimics the flight of the hummingbird
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents, if not to imitate obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
CEATEC in Japan introduced an amazing project that inspired Nissan engineers to create new systems to prevent accidents.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C-type biomimetic system, a mini car equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protection shield," Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, told the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers adopted the idea of the laser-controlled distance gauge.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of vision within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the author robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it didn’t, the author robot couldn’t react fast enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the author robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield – a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable at the moment.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, the evasion, unlike the bees, can not take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and that is only in the direction of the tire's turnability.
While there are endless possibilities for the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers could only use the rotation or acceleration and deceleration of the author robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy-efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained, it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, less on the processing of data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond accordingly to them.
It doesn’t have to store them or produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous manoeuvres, so it requires only a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously steering the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the destination.
