Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historic cinemas close because of the beneficiary multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This image by director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the great urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of the cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, in the long run means the death for the cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
“It’s like losing a friend with whom you walk a piece of street full of emotions,” says the director of the film “Nuovo Cinema Paradiso”, who won him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago. It’s the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a well-lost cinema forever.
The numbers supplied by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the tremendous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have been shut down; these teaks paid for the most part the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are the Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This indicates that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational manner," says Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but the first thing is the preservation of the already existing one, because if a hall closes in the city, not all its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here is still the lack of budget for the fund of the trade association: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral standpoint that the government does not abide by existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be in need.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to decide to protect the ancient cinemas by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first of its kind in Italy to protect and support the traditional cinemas, both in the historic center and in the periphery.
Foreseen measures also include tax benefits for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public with regard to local transport: it will be allowed to drive into the traffic-limited areas of the center and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
“It is a pleasant initiative,” says Giuseppe Tornatore, “I hope that other cities will follow our example and also design new concepts.
