When the energy springs out of the waves, the big ones suddenly run up
It’s a non-sittering source of money that covers over 70% of the planet’s surface and only now seems the world’s big energy companies to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone now looks at, and also seeks to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of drawing energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; these studies have not been significantly intensified since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was lost, but now environmental organizations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy demand could be covered by the energy generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equal to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to now rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was released, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are relying on marine energy generation.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said the spokesman for a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and weighs off the possibility of working with us.”
This is about the procurement of an approval from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that in Alaska, the US continues to produce oil and that President Bush has only recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers speak of an increasing interest.
Still improved technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still underway, not least because the latest doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as that in Portugal and Scotland are rather small and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with much greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected boxes.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the boxes up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmer via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn drives a generator.
The current is sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for government authorization, and some of the energy obtained could also be used for military installations.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a warehouse and a parking lot using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotation movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Recovery Research, there is a special interest in the potential that lies in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, sunlight and also waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely the tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, have already invested $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
